<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>



<section xml:id="lesson4_4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Summary</title>

    
<p>
To summarize, let's step through the example you just solved. We want to understand
the behavior we see when we place a measurement betweeen two H gates.</p>
<p>  <image source="L4.3-measure-in-h-gate-2.png" width="90%" /> </p>


<p> That measurement collapses the superposition after the first H gate, so the 
second H gate is receiving a qubit that is either <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m>, not a qubit in superposition.
The second H gate then places the qubit back into superposition, but the phase is unknown. 
The second measurement then collapses the superposition, 
and the outcome is either <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m> with equal probability.</p>

<p>  <image source="L4.3-summary-2.png" width="90%" /> </p>

<p> If there is no measurement between the H gates, however, the second H gate receives an input that is in superposition 
with a 50/50 probability of being <m>\ket{0}</m> or <m>\ket{1}</m> and phase corresponding to whether the initial
input was black or white. The second H gate then places the qubit back into a state that is either <m>\ket{0}</m> 
or <m>\ket{1}</m> with 100% probability, depending on the initial input.</p>


<p>  <image source="L4.3-summary-1.png" width="90%" /> </p>

  

</section>